b'' b'this may be a very naive question but is there any basis for the' b'claim that a cpu will get hotter when a computationally intensive' b'job is running?' b'' b'i totally agree with your friend, since when the cpu is apparently idle' b'it is still in fact churning away millions of instructions per second' b'(checking for keyboard input for instance).' b'' b"the exception to this is for cpu's used in laptops, where the cpu can" b'enter an idle state where it is just preserving its current status but' b'doing absolutely nothing. in this case it needs a hardware interrupt' b'to get it going again.' b'' b'actually, the iapx86 family has a halt instruction that causes the cpu to' b'cease processing instructions. the cpu resumes processing either by being' b'reset or by receiving an external (hardware) interrupt. this is different' b'from the power management facilities victor mentions. of course, whether an' b"operating system's idle loop uses the halt instruction is another matter" b'entirely.' b'--' b'kenneth r. ballou\t\t\t\tvoice:\t\t b'oberon software, inc.\t\t\t\tfax:\t\t b'' b'the views and opinions expressed above are my own and do not necessarily' b'reflect those of my employer.' 